Name: Main switch
Help:
Start / stop of refrigeration. 
With this setting refrigeration can be started, stopped or a manual override of the outputs can be allowed. (For manual control the value is set at -1. Then the outputs can be force controlled. Start / stop of refrigeration can also be accomplished with the external switch function connected to a DI input.
Stopped control will give a ”Standby alarm.

Name: Application mode
Help:
Selection of application 
The controller covers several applications for control of a refrigerated case. Here you set which of the possible applications is required.
This menu can only be set when regulation is stopped, i.e. “r12 Main Switch” is set to 0.

Name: Temperature sensor type
Help:
Sensor type for S3, S4 and S5. 
Normally a Pt 1000 sensor with great signal accuracy is used. But you can also use a sensor with another signal accuracy. That may either be a PTC sensor (1000 ohm at 25°C) All the mounted sensors S3-S5 must be of the same type. 
0 = Pt 1000
1 = PTC 1000
2 = NTC 5k
3 = NTC 10k

Name: Defrost method
Help: Here you set whether defrost is to be accomplished with electricity, gas, air circulation or (none).  During defrost the defrost relay will be cut in.

Name: Defrost stop method
Help: Here you define whether a defrost sequence is to be stopped by time or a temperature sensor

Name: Defrost stop temperature
Help:
The defrost is stopped at a given temperature which is measured with a sensor (the sensor is defined in d10). 
The temperature value is set.

Enum: 1:Thermostat air,2:Alarm air,3:S3 Air ON evap.,4:S6 Product temp.

Name: Network address
Help: Network address of the controller

Name: Service pin
Help:
If the controller is built into a LonWorks network with data communication, it must have an address, and the system manager must know this address.
The address is sent to the system manager when the menu is set in pos. ON. IMPORTANT: Before you set o04, you MUST set the application mode of the controller (The function is not used when the data communication is MODBUS)

Name: Thermostat band
Help:
Readout of which thermostat used for regulation: 

1= Thermostat band 1
2= Thermostat band 2

Name: Food temperature A
Help: Read out of food temperature

Name: Thermostat mode
Help:
Here it is defined how the thermostat is to operate. Either as an ordinary ON/OFF thermostat or as a modulating thermostat.
When operation is ”modulating” the valve will limit the flow of refrigerant so that the temperature variation will be less than for the ON/OFF thermostat.
The differential (r01) must not be set lower than 2K for ""modulating"".
In a decentralised plant you must select the ON/OFF thermostat setting."

Name: Ther. band 1/Cutout
Help:
Set point. 
The thermostat’s cutout value when the given thermostat band is in use

Name: Ther. band 2/Cutout
Help:
Set point. 
The thermostat’s cutout value when the given thermostat band is in use

Name: Ther. band 1 /Differential
Help: When the temperature is higher than the reference + the set differential, the compressor relay will be cut in. It will cut out again when the temperature comes down to the set reference."

Name: Max cutout limit
Help:
Setpoint limitation - 
The controller’s setting range for the setpoint may be narrowed down, so that much too high or much too low values are not set accidentally - with resulting damages.
To avoid a too high setting of the setpoint, the max. allowable reference value may be lowered

Name: Min cutout limit
Help:
Setpoint limitation - 
The controller’s setting range for the setpoint may be narrowed down, so that much too high or much too low values are not set accidentally - with resulting damages.
To avoid a too low setting of the setpoint, the min. allowable reference value may be increased

Name: Thermostat S4 %
Help:
Selection of thermostat sensor. 
Here you define the sensor the thermostat is to use for its control function. S3, S4, or a combination of them. With the setting 0%, only S3 is used. With 100%, only S4.

Name: Thermostat S4 % night
Help:
Selection of thermostat sensor S4% during night operation with night blinds. 
Here you define the sensor the thermostat is to use for its control function. S3, S4, or a combination of them. With the setting 0%, only S3 is used. With 100%, only S4.

Name: Night offset
Help:
Night setback value.
The thermostat’s reference will be the setpoint plus this value when the controller changes over to night operation.

Name: S4 Frost protection
Help: Frost protection on S4 air temperature. If the S4 temperature sensors measures a temperature lower than the set limit, refrigeration will be stopped in order to protect produce from ice formation. Refrigeration will start again when the S4 temperature has risen 2K above the set limit

Name: Air heater neutralzone
Help:
Heat function. 
Set the width of the Neutral Zone for changeover from cooling to heating "

Name: Air heater start delay
Help:
Time delay on transition from refrigeration phase to heating phase 
(there is not time delay on transition from heating phase to refrigeration phase)

Name: Melt interval
Help:
Melt function. 
Only for control of MT cases/rooms (-5 to +10°C). The function ensures that the evaporator will not be blocked by frost. Here you set how often the function is to stop the refrigeration and hence transform the frost to water (or ice if there is too much frost).

Name: Melt period
Help:
Melt period. 
Here you set how long an on-going melt function is to last

Name: Alarm status
Help: Actual alarm status

Name: Alarm air temp. A
Help: Measured temperature for alarm thermostat

Name: Alarm air temp. B
Help: Measured temperature for alarm thermostat

Name: S6 Product temp. A
Help: Actual sensor value

Name: Reset all alarms
Help: Command for resetting all alarms

Name: Alarm sensor S4% A
Help:
Signal to the alarm thermostat 
Here you have to define the ratio between the sensors which the alarm thermostat has to use. S3, S4 or a combination of the two. 
With setting 0% only S3 is used. With 100% only S4 is used

Name: Ther. band 1 /High alarm limit
Help:
Upper alarm limit. 
Here you set when the alarm for high temperature is to start. The limit value is set in absolute value.  
The limit value will be raised with the night offset during night operation.

Name: Ther. band 1 /Low alarm limit
Help:
Lower alarm limit. 
Here you set when the alarm for low temperature is to start. The limit value is set in absolute value

Name: Ther. band 2 /High alarm limit
Help:
Upper alarm limit. 
Here you set when the alarm for high temperature is to start. The limit value is set in absolute value.  
The limit value will be raised with the night offset during night operation.

Name: Ther. band 2 /Low alarm limit
Help:
Lower alarm limit. 
Here you set when the alarm for low temperature is to start. The limit value is set in absolute value

Name: Alarm delay A
Help:
Alarm delay (short alarm delay on air temperature)
. If the upper or the lower alarm limit values are exceeded, a timer function will commence. The alarm will not become active until the set time delay has been passed. 
The time delay is set in minutes

Name: Alarm delay pulldown A
Help:
Time delay for cooling (long alarm delay)
This time delay is used during start-up, during defrost, immediately after a defrost. There will be change-over to the normal time delay when the temperature has dropped below the set upper alarm limit. 
The time delay is set in minutes

Name: Alarm delay B
Help:
Alarm delay (short alarm delay on air temperature)
. If the upper or the lower alarm limit values are exceeded, a timer function will commence. The alarm will not become active until the set time delay has been passed. 
The time delay is set in minutes

Name: Ther. band 1 /S6 High alarm limit
Help: Upper alarm limit for S6 product temperature

Name: Ther. band 1 /S6 Low alarm limit
Help: Lower alarm limit for S6 product temperature

Name: Ther. band 2 /S6 High alarm limit
Help: Upper alarm limit for S6 product temperature

Name: Ther. band 2 /S6 Low alarm limit
Help: Lower alarm limit for S6 product temperature

Name: S6 Alarm delay
Help:
S6 temperature alarm delay 
The alarm is activated if one of the relevant alarm limits is exceeded. The time delay is set in minutes. 
(Alarms will not activate when the setting is set to the maximum value.)

Name: S6 Alarm delay pulldown
Help:
Time delay on S6 (product sensor) for pull-down (long alarm delay)
This time delay is used for start-up, during defrosting, immediately after a defrost and after an appliance clean. 
A change is carried out to standard time delay (A26) when the temperature has reached below the set upper alarm limit. The time delay is set in minutes.

Name: Door open alarm delay
Help:
Time delay for door alarm
The time delay is set in minutes.

Name: Door restart inj. delay
Help:
Start of refrigeration when door is open 
If the door has been left open, refrigeration must be started after a set time. That time can be set here.

Name: Alarm delay DI 1
Help: Time delay for digital input alarm

Name: Alarm delay DI 2
Help: Time delay for digital input alarm

Name: Humidity cutin SP
Help: Set point for the humidity control. If the relative humidity goes below the set point the humidifier is started

Name: Humidity differential
Help: Differential for stopping humidifier. Humidification is stopped when the humidity has increased with the set differntial above the set point

Name: Humidity high alarm limit
Help: High alarm limit for relative humidity

Name: Humidity low alarm limit
Help: Low alarm limit for relative humidity

Name: Humidity alarm delay
Help: Delay of high and low humidity alarms

Name: Humidity ctrl. at defrost
Help:
Select how to control humidity during defrost:
No: Humidity control is stopped during defrost
Yes: Normal humidity control is running during defrost

Name: AKV valve opening degree
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Pe Evap. pressure A
Help: Actual sensor signal

Name: Te Evap. temp. A
Help: Temperature converted from pressure

Name: S2 Gas outlet A
Help: Actual sensor value

Name: Superheat
Help: Readout of actual superheat

Name: Superheat reference
Help: Read out of the actual superheat reference

Name: Min superheat limit
Help: Min. value for the superheat reference

Name: Max superheat limit
Help: Max. value for the superheat reference

Name: MOP temperature
Help:
MOP temperature 
If no MOP function is required, select highest value, which corresponds to OFF

Name: AKV Period time
Help:
AKV valve’s time period in seconds 
Should only be set to a lower value if it is a decentralised plant and the suction  pressure fluctuates a lot and in line with the opening of the AKV valve.

Name: Min superheat limit flood
Help: Min. value for the superheat reference during flooded operation

Name: Max superheat limit flood
Help: Max. value for the superheat reference during flooded operation

Name: Defrost sensor temperature
Help: Actual temperature of selected defrost stop sensor

Name: S5 Evaporator A
Help: Actual sensor value

Name: S5 Evaporator B
Help: Actual sensor value

Name: Defrost time
Help: Read the duration of the ongoing defrost or the duration of the last completed defrost.

Name: Defrost A
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Defrost B
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Adaptive defrost state
Help: Actual state of the adaptive defrost function

Name: Accumulated defrosts
Help: Number of defrosts carried out since the initial power up or since the resetting of the function

Name: Accumulated skipped defrosts
Help: Number of defrosts skipped since the initial power up or since the resetting of the function

Name: Tc temp. average
Help: Average value of the condensing temperature signal distributed via the system manager to the case controllers that are using adaptive defrost. At transcritical CO2 sites the receiver pressure is distributed to the case controllers. Function needs to be set up in the system manager.

Name: Start defrost
Help: Command for starting a defrost

Name: Max defrost time
Help: This setting is a safety time so that the defrost will be stopped if there has not already been a stop based on temperature or via coordinated defrost.

Name: Defrost start interval
Help:
The function is zeroset and will start the timer function at each defrost start. When the time has expired the function will start a defrost. 
The function is used as a simple defrost start, or it may be used as a safeguard if the normal signal fails to appear. 
If master/slave defrost without clock function or without data communication is used, the interval time will be used as max. time between defrosts. 
If a defrost start via data communcation does not take place, the interval time will be used as max. time between defrosts.
When there is defrost with clock function or data communication, the interval time must be set for a somewhat longer period of time than the planned one.  In connection with power failure the interval time will be maintained, and when the power returns the interval time will continue from the maintained value. 
he interval time is not active when set to 0

Name: Time staggering power up
Help:
Time staggering for defrost cutins during start-up 
The function is only relevant if you have several refrigeration appliances or groups where you want the defrost to be staggered in relation to one another. The function is furthermore only relevant if you have chosen defrost with interval start. The function delays the interval time by the set number of minutes, but it only does it once, and this at the very first defrost taking place when voltage is connected to the controller. 
The function will be active after each and every power failure.

Name: Max thermostat runtime
Help:
Defrost on demand – aggregate refrigeration time 
Set here is the refrigeration time allowed without defrosts. If the time is passed, a defrost will be started. With setting = 0 the function is cut out.

Name: Pump down delay
Help: Set the time where the evaporator is emptied of refrigerant prior to the defrost.

Name: Drip off time
Help: Here you set the time that is to elapse from a defrost and until the compressor is to start again. (The time when water drips off the evaporator).

Name: Max hold time
Help:
Max. standby time after coordinated defrost 
When a controller has completed a defrost it will wait for a signal which tells that the refrigeration may be resumed. If this signal fails to appear for one reason or another, the controller will itself start the refrigeration when this standby time has elapsed.

Name: Drain delay
Help:
Drain delay (only in connection with hotgas) 
Set the time where the evaporator is emptied of condensed refrigerant after the defrost.

Name: Fan ctrl. during defrost
Help:
Fan cut in during defrost 
Here you can set whether fan is to operate during defrost.
0: Stopped (Runs during pump down)

1: Running (stopped during  "fan delay")

2: Running during pump down and defrost. After that stopped

3: Running during pump down and defrost until defrost stop sensor reaches fan stop temperature limit

Name: Fan start delay
Help:
Delay of fan start after defrost
Here you set the time that is to elapse from compressor start after a defrost and until the fan may start again. (The time when water is “tied” to the evaporator).

Name: Fan start temp.
Help: The fan may also be started a little earlier than mentioned under “Delay of fan start after defrost”, if the defrost sensor S5 registers a lower value than the one set here.

Name: Fan stop temp.
Help: If the fan control during defrost has been set up for it, the fans can be stopped during the defrost if the defrost sensor exceeds the set temperature limit

Name: Railheat at defrost
Help:
Define how railheat is controlled during defrost
0: Railheat is OFF all the time
1: Railheat is ON all the time
2: Normal railheat control

Name: Display delay after defrost
Help: Set the maximum time the display should show the defrost code "-d-" after a defrost. The normal temperature readout is normally started when the temperature in the case is OK again or if a high temperature alarm is raised.

Name: Adaptive defrost mode
Help:
An adaptive defrosting is an extra defrost in addition to the scheduled defrosts or skips a scheduled defrost.  
Here the adaptive defrost is set for when it can come into operation if the need arises: 
0: Never, 
1: Never, but triggers an alarm in the case of icing up 
2: Scheduled defrosts during day time can be skipped. 
3: Scheduled defrosts during day and night time can be skipped. 
4: All schedules are carried out + extra if it is registered that it is required. 
(Temporary setting to 0FF will reset the recorded values.)

Name: Compressor 1
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Compressor 2
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Min ON time
Help:
Running times 
To prevent irregular operation, values can be set for the time the compressor is to run once it has been started. And for how long it at least has to be stopped.
Min. ON-time (in minutes)

Name: Min OFF time
Help:
Running times 
To prevent irregular operation, values can be set for the time the compressor is to run once it has been started. And for how long it at least has to be stopped.
Min. OFF-time (in minutes)

Name: Delay between steps
Help:
Time delay for couplings of two compressors 
Settings indicate the time that has to elapse from the first relay cuts in and until the next relay has to cut in.

Name: Step ctrl. mode
Help: Selection of step control mode for compressors. At sequential mode compressor 1 will always be the first to start and the last to stop. In cyclic mode the run time between the compressor will be equalized.

Name: Fan
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Fan ECO
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Fan pulsing mode
Help:
Pulse operation of fan 
0: No pulse operation 
1: Pulse operation when the thermostat does not call for refrigeration 
2: Pulse operation when the thermostat does not call for refrigeration, but only during night operation

Name: Fan cycle time
Help:
Pulse operation period for fan 
Here the overall pulse time is set. The sum of ON-to and OFF time.

Name: Fan ON time
Help:
ON time for fan 
Here the % part of the period the fans are to be in operation is set.

Name: Fan stop high S5 temp.
Help:
Fan stop temperature 
The function stops the fans in an error situation, so that they will not provide power to the appliance. If the defrost sensor registers a higher temperature than the one set here, the fans will be stopped. There will be re-start at 2 K below the setting. 
The function is not active during a defrost or start-up after a defrost.
With setting +50°C the function is interrupted.

Name: Fan at forced closing
Enum: 0:OFF,1:ON,2:OFF and no defrost,3:ON and no defrost
ChineseEnum: 0:OFF,1:ON,2:OFF and no defrost,3:ON and no defrost
Help:
You can set whether fans should be operational or stopped if the function "Forced closing" is activated here. 
0: Fans are OFF
1: Fans are ON
2: Fans are OFF and defrost is not permitted
3: Fans are ON and defrost is not permitted

Name: Dewpoint
Help: Actual dewpoint received from system manager via network

Name: Railheat duty cycle
Help: Readout of the actual rail heat effect in %

Name: Railheat ctrl. mode
Help:
The rail heat can be controlled in several ways: 

0: Railheat is running all the time 

1: Pulse control is used with a timer function following the day/night operation (o41 and o42) 

2: Pulse control is used with a dew point function. This function requires that a signal is received about the dew point value. The value is measured by a system manager and sent to the controller via the data communication.

Name: Railheat ON day
Help: Railheat control during day time. The ON period is set as a percentage of the cycle time

Name: Railheat ON night
Help: Railheat control during night time. The ON period is set as a percentage of the cycle time

Name: Railheat cycle time
Help: Periodtime for pulsing of railheat

Name: Railheat PWM cycle time
Help: Periodtime for railheat control when using an analogue PWM output

Name: Railheat Min ON

Lowest permitted rail heat effect 
Here the % part of the effect to be achieved when the dew point value is minimum.

Name: Dewpoint min limit
Help: Dew point value where the rail heat is running at minimum heat

Name: Dewpoint max  limit
Help: Dew point value where the rail heat is maximum

Name: Blinds
Help: Actual status of output function

Name: Light control mode
Help:
Configuration of light function
1) Light is controlled via  day/night status 
2) Light is controlled via data communication and "Light remote o39" 
3) Light is controlled by door contact on DI input. When the door is opened the relay will cut in. When the door is closed again there will be a time delay of two minutes before the light is switched off. 
4) As "2" but if there are any 15-minute network errors, the light will switch on and the night blind will open. 
5) Light is controlled via DI input signal

Name: Light ctrl. at standby
Help:
Light and night blinds definition 
0: Light is switched off and night blinds are open when the main switch is off 
1: Light and night blinds are independent of main switch.

Name: Blinds closing delay
Help: Time delay from when blinds have been opened manually until they close again

Name: Blinds closing fan stop
Help: Time required for closing night blinds in which the fans will be stopped

Name: Case cleaning
Help:
The status of the function can be followed here or the function can be started manually.
0 = Normal operation (no cleaning) 
1 = Cleaning with fans operating. All other outputs are Off. 
2 = Cleaning with stopped fans. All outputs are Off. 
If the function is controlled by a digital input signal, the relevant status can be seen here in the menu.
